2026-04-11 | Minimum Distance of Equal Triplet

Question:
•	You are given an array nums.  
•	A valid triplet:
		three indices i, j, k  
		such that nums[i] == nums[j] == nums[k]  

•	Distance formula:
		|i - j| + |j - k| + |k - i|  

•	Goal:
		find minimum distance among all valid triplets.

	Key Insight
For sorted indices i < j < k:
		distance = (j-i) + (k-j) + (k-i)
				 = 2 × (k - i)

So:
→ we only need to minimize (k - i)

→ choose **3 closest occurrences** of same value.

	Approach
1.	Group indices by value:
		value → list of indices  

2.	For each value:
		if occurrences < 3 → skip  

3.	Use sliding window of size 3:
		for i from 0 to size-3:
			dist = 2 × (v[i+2] - v[i])  

4.	Take minimum across all values  

5.	If no valid triplet → return -1  

	Time Complexity
	O(n)

	Space Complexity
	O(n)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    int minimumDistance(vector<int>& nums) {

        unordered_map<int, vector<int>> mp;

        for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++){
            mp[nums[i]].push_back(i);
        }

        int ans = INT_MAX;

        for(auto &it : mp){

            auto &v = it.second;

            if(v.size() < 3) continue;

            for(int i = 0; i + 2 < v.size(); i++){
                int dist = 2 * (v[i+2] - v[i]);
                ans = min(ans, dist);
            }
        }

        return ans == INT_MAX ? -1 : ans;
    }
};

	Key Insight
The complex distance formula simplifies to:
		2 × (k - i)  

So problem reduces to:
		finding closest 3 occurrences of same number  

This makes solution efficient using hashing + sliding window.
